description: Project-wide quality, Tailwind-only styling, and docs-first implementation standards.
alwaysApply: true
---

## Dependency Injection Scope

- **No `providedIn: 'root'` for app services**: Do not register application-defined services with `providedIn: 'root'`. Instead, scope services at the **route**, **feature**, or **component** level using Angular provider configuration.
- **Module/feature scoping**: Prefer feature-level providers that are attached to routes or feature entrypoints. This keeps services easier to reason about, more testable, and more tree-shakeable.
- **Exceptions**: It is acceptable for Angular core and third-party libraries to use `providedIn: 'root'` internally; do not attempt to change those.

## Quality & Documentation First

- **Docs before code**: Before using or configuring any external package (Tailwind, PrimeNG, Firebase, Angular features, etc.), review its **official documentation** for the current major version and follow recommended patterns.
- **Code quality over speed**: Prefer clear, well-structured, and well-typed implementations over quick hacks or partial solutions. Avoid speculative shortcuts that deviate from documented usage.
- **Align with Anafora design**: When adjusting the theme or layout, keep the calm, desert-retreat aesthetic of the main Anafora site (`https://anafora.org/`) in mind rather than default UI presets.

## Styling & Theming

- **Tailwind-only styles**: Do **not** introduce new `.scss` files or custom SCSS code. All new styling must use Tailwind utility classes, component utilities, or configuration.
- **Tailwind configuration**:
  - Use `tailwind.config.ts` as the single source of truth for theme tokens (colors, shadows, radii, etc.).
  - Keep `src/styles.scss` limited to Tailwind entry, light global resets, and small utility classes that use `@apply`—no bespoke design systems in SCSS.
- **Glassmorphism**:
  - Reuse the shared glassmorphism utilities (e.g. `app-bg`, `card-glass`, `btn-primary`, `btn-ghost`, `input-glass`, `text-muted`) instead of re-inventing similar patterns.
  - Prefer layered, translucent surfaces with subtle blur and warm accent colors over flat solid panels, matching the retreat aesthetic.

## Auth, Roles, and Security

- **Firebase usage**:
  - Use the centralized helpers from `src/app/core/config/firebase.config.ts` instead of initializing Firebase ad hoc.
  - Wrap Firebase Auth and Firestore access behind dedicated services (e.g. `AuthService`) that expose signals/observables and well-typed domain models.
- **Roles**:
  - Treat `superAdmin`, `admin`, and `user` as a strict hierarchy, encoded via a shared `Role` type and comparison helpers.
  - Read roles from **custom claims** and mirrored Firestore `users` documents; do not attempt to set custom claims directly from the client—defer that to secure backend/Cloud Functions.
- **Guards**:
  - Use functional route guards for authentication and role checks, returning `UrlTree` redirects rather than side-effecting navigation where possible.

